4. Anchovies are the shit and should be added to everything
5. Ginger does not have to be peeled
6. The ends of garlic cloves don't need to be trimmed
7. Keeping roots or skins on alliums are totes fine

Allison: Life Hack for you, get silicon ice cube trays, fill them with water and place them in your freezer, then use the ice cubes in them when they freeze to shock your veggies, its also good for making chilled lemonade in our steaming hot apartment in the Summer: If your chicken skin is not staying crispy then you didn't get it crispy enough initially, try a hotter oven temp while tenting the chicken with foil then at the last 15 minutes of roasting you remove the aluminum foil tent and the skin gets super crispy, it will stay crispy for a while unless you are letting it rest too long (which is known as cooling t down, instead of resting), don't pour liquids on the crispy skin, pour it on the meat.

text: I literally made this LAST NIGHT and I think it's v important to say that contrary to the idea that this is an 'occupied the whole time' dish, it's actually perfect to make in advance! You can make the sauces, blanch the veg & prep the chicken hours ahead and just pop the chicken in 90 mins before you plan to eat. Take it out of the oven, let it rest while you take your veg out of the fridge and arrange on a plate to take the chill off, carve that bad by up and you're good to go! A perfect (and delicious!) dinner party meal :)

Qq: is it sanitary to reuse a bowl of salt that raw, meaty fingers have been in? text: Salt dehydrates cells.  Many types of bacteria won't survive in a high salt environment (or will at least grow/reproduce more slowly).  Unless your hands are really dripping, it also seems more likely to have extra salt stuck to your hands than excessive meat juice contaminating your salt.  Chefs also tend to use a lot of salt so that bowl is being emptied fairly quickly.  I think many chefs also try to keep one hand clean (i.e. free of raw meat juice) for seasoning purposes.  But it is probably a combination of many factors... science, technique, editing.
